Star Trek Into Darkness may not have been the worst of the Star Trek 
movies, but it is certainly the dumbest. From the transwarp transporter 
that effectively negates the need for starships to the miracle, life 
restoring blood , to  the flipped Warp Core Death Scene, it was an abortion 
that lived and it should have died in the womb from it's own stupidity. An 
article posted today on Yahoo reports that the title of the next movie in 
the series is going to be "Star Trek Beyond". Judging by the title alone, 
we're in for more stupidity. It's hard to imagine a movie that's stupider 
than Into Darkness, but I believe that the writers of Star Trek Beyond will 
skillfully accomplish that feat.﻿

comments.text: What's the difference between Star Trek and Star Wars?﻿
comments.author: Jayanth S

comments.text:
+Jayanth S Surprisingly, a HUGE amount of difference. (Well, if you go by 
the original series of Star Trek.) Star Trek is supposed to be the future 
of Earth in the 23rd century. The starship Enterprise goes on a mission to 
explore the outer regions of space and contact other worlds. Star Wars is 
about an entirely different galaxy in another part of the universe where a 
group of people try to take down their evil ruler and set up a better 
government. There is also quite a bit of difference in the tone and style 
of each series as well as the extremely different technology, space 
shuttles, planets, and lifestyle of the characters.

comments.text:
I, as someone new to the Star Trek franchise, liked this movie. The women 
made me want to smash my head and Captain Kirk made me cringe in almost 
every scene, but I genuinely enjoyed Benedict Cumberbatch's performance. I 
don't know whether this is a negative point for the movie or not, but at 
some point, I just stopped seeing him as a villain. Eventhough everyone 
else other than scotty made me cringe, I watched and enjoyed the movie 
because of BC. HOWEVER, his performance would've been great for someone 
called William Edward Michaelson, not Khan. I'm from the middle east and I 
was trying to figure out how on earth the most british guy on earth, with 
the bluest eyes and palest skin could possibly be called "Khan". The 
casting director made the best decision in the wrongest direction, 'cause 
let's be serious, it would've been way worse if almost any other white 
actor was playing him.﻿
